00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:28.710
PROFESSOR: I want to talk a
little bit about producing

00:00:28.710 --> 00:00:35.340
and realizing your
visions, and give

00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:40.080
an example of some of the things
that Chris was talking about.

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:44.170
So we shot a video on how
engines worked, and there

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:47.766
is a part of the video where
the two creators were talking

00:00:47.766 --> 00:00:49.140
about how a turbine
engine works.

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:51.400
And I think I might have
told this story before,

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:54.642
about how we ended up finding
like an actual Boeing engine.

00:00:54.642 --> 00:00:56.100
But there are a
lot of ways that we

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:57.308
could have filmed this scene.

00:00:57.308 --> 00:01:02.220
We could have animated it, we
could have done a wide frame

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:05.820
shot with animation overlay,
like I showed you with George's

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:08.050
[INAUDIBLE] videos.

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:10.840
We could have done B-roll,
so we could have just done

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:12.370
like close up
shots of the engine

00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:15.560
while you heard Luke
explaining how it worked,

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:16.550
with his voiceover.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:19.380
Or we could have done
a live explanation,

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:20.630
which is what we went with.

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:26.730
So this is how George shot Luke.

00:01:26.730 --> 00:01:28.880
We went with the
traditional thirds framing.

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:31.430
Again, this isn't necessarily
a rule that you have to go by,

00:01:31.430 --> 00:01:34.200
it just worked really
well for this scene.

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.690
And we went with
this because it also

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:42.070
gave us the ability to do sort
of an interesting point of view

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:42.570
shot.

00:01:42.570 --> 00:01:45.100
The point of view isn't
from the narrator,

00:01:45.100 --> 00:01:46.550
it's actually from the viewer.

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:49.670
So I'll show you the
clip in a second.

00:01:49.670 --> 00:01:51.860
But essentially, we
did one long take

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:55.280
where George moved his
camera as Luke was explaining

00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:56.460
the parts of the engine.

00:01:56.460 --> 00:02:00.520
So we wanted it to feel like
the camera was basically

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:05.410
where a person would be if Luke
was explaining how a turbine

00:02:05.410 --> 00:02:08.891
engine works to a
person standing there.

00:02:08.891 --> 00:02:10.339
LUKE: --won't work.

00:02:10.339 --> 00:02:11.880
FEMALE IN VIDEO:
What you really need

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:14.952
is one engine that can
produce enough horsepower

00:02:14.952 --> 00:02:15.660
to fly the plane.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:19.760
A turbine engine is capable
of much more horse power

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:21.810
than a piston engine
because of the way

00:02:21.810 --> 00:02:24.805
it uses giant fans
to compress the air.

00:02:24.805 --> 00:02:26.180
LUKE: At the front
of the turbine

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:29.200
engine is an intake
fan which spins

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:32.800
and brings a huge amount of air
into the front of the engine.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:34.970
As we move backwards
through the engine,

00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:38.460
a series of compressor blades
makes that air more and more

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:40.850
compressed, until we get here.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.500
And here, fuel is
introduced and burned.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:46.270
And that hot, high
pressure flow gets sent

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:47.480
out the back of the engine.

00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:49.520
And that makes the
thrust of the engine.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.350
But at the same time,
that flow passes

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:54.760
through a series of four
or five turbine blades,

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:56.430
and those blades are
connected directly

00:02:56.430 --> 00:02:58.620
to a shaft at the
middle of the engine.

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.280
That shaft runs all the
way back to the front

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:03.420
and spins the intake fan.

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:07.070
That's what keeps
the engine running.

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:09.380
PROFESSOR: So that shot
worked because Luke

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:12.330
was very comfortable explaining
that in one long take.

00:03:12.330 --> 00:03:15.580
He actually ad libbed
that whole thing.

00:03:15.580 --> 00:03:18.370
And I can see that it's a
lot of information at once,

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:20.620
so maybe it would have been
better to do an animation.

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:22.869
We certainly could've done
it a lot of different ways.

00:03:22.869 --> 00:03:24.450
But what I like
about that shot is

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:26.570
that if you were
just standing there,

00:03:26.570 --> 00:03:29.290
and Luke was
explaining it to you,

00:03:29.290 --> 00:03:31.500
the camera would basically
be your eyes, right?

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:33.160
Like you would walk
along with him,

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:36.270
and you would look down at the
engine when he pointed to it,

00:03:36.270 --> 00:03:38.160
you would look back up at him.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:41.090
So that's the type of movement
that Chris was talking about

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:43.000
that you can introduce
to your video.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.057
It would be really different
if we had just set up a tripod

00:03:46.057 --> 00:03:47.890
and had Luke explain
the whole thing, right?

00:03:47.890 --> 00:03:50.417
Like it would have been a
very different experience.

00:03:50.417 --> 00:03:51.371
GUEST SPEAKER: And it's
not random movement,

00:03:51.371 --> 00:03:53.040
it's obviously very
directed, which

00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:55.187
is the key to many of
these kinds of things.

00:03:55.187 --> 00:03:56.387
It's not [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:56.387 --> 00:03:57.095
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:03:57.095 --> 00:04:01.280
Like we wanted to really follow
what the natural person would

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:05.095
do if they were just standing
there talking to Luke.

00:04:05.095 --> 00:04:06.970
I want to talk about
the lighting real quick.

00:04:06.970 --> 00:04:10.000
So we were in an
airplane hangar,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:11.790
and it was like
one in the morning,

00:04:11.790 --> 00:04:13.380
so it was super dark outside.

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:16.350
I mean, we mostly relied
on the overhead lights.

00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:20.660
I don't actually know if we
lit this with anything else.

00:04:20.660 --> 00:04:23.050
Because it's super
bright in there.

00:04:23.050 --> 00:04:25.170
So you don't need
super fancy equipment

00:04:25.170 --> 00:04:30.170
to achieve the videos that
you guys are going to do.

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:32.930
So to talk a little bit
more about producing,

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:35.324
when you think of
directing I feel

00:04:35.324 --> 00:04:37.740
like that's what most people
think of when making a video.

00:04:37.740 --> 00:04:39.948
And directing is a lot about
thinking in the present.

00:04:39.948 --> 00:04:43.500
So you're coaching the host,
you're coaching the talent,

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.697
telling them what to do
right there in that moment.

00:04:45.697 --> 00:04:47.530
You're thinking about
what the framing looks

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:48.690
like in that moment.

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:51.570
Producing is a lot about
thinking about the future,

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:55.420
anticipating what's coming
next, the mistakes that you're

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:56.240
going to make.

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:00.807
So on a practical level it's a
lot of check boxes, basically.

00:05:00.807 --> 00:05:02.390
You're thinking about
where am I going

00:05:02.390 --> 00:05:04.890
to film, what are my backups
going to be, where am I

00:05:04.890 --> 00:05:06.570
going to record voice over?

00:05:06.570 --> 00:05:10.430
My experience filming at MIT is
that it is incredibly difficult

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:15.730
to find a quiet place on campus
to record clean voiceover.

00:05:15.730 --> 00:05:17.864
And if you're having
trouble finding a spot,

00:05:17.864 --> 00:05:19.030
come talk to me at any time.

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:20.429
I can help you with that.

00:05:20.429 --> 00:05:21.762
AUDIENCE: What do you mean that?

00:05:21.762 --> 00:05:23.634
Why do you mean that?

00:05:23.634 --> 00:05:25.550
PROFESSOR: So take this
classroom for example,

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:30.050
most of the spaces on campus
have this hum overhead.

00:05:30.050 --> 00:05:32.620
And most of you guys will be
relying on the lavalier mic,

00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:34.330
so it's not as bad.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:38.162
But there's just a lot
of background noise

00:05:38.162 --> 00:05:41.420
that is on campus.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:44.190
So if you're just
recording plain voice over

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:47.080
that you want to
use in your video,

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:48.580
it would be more
ideal if you could

00:05:48.580 --> 00:05:52.440
get something that's quieter
than this room, for example.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:55.660
So you're thinking
in checklists,

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.920
and some of the boxes
are a little more inane,

00:05:57.920 --> 00:05:59.970
like did we shoot
all of the scenes?

00:05:59.970 --> 00:06:01.890
Which sounds stupid,
but I actually

00:06:01.890 --> 00:06:03.850
missed that on my own video.

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:06.520
I forgot to film
one of the scenes.

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:07.910
And then, did we
get clean audio?

00:06:07.910 --> 00:06:11.210
So a tip that I would
recommend for you guys

00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:14.050
is, even after you film
all of your scenes,

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:18.640
I would sit down and just record
voiceover of your entire script

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:20.450
in a separate audio file.

00:06:20.450 --> 00:06:22.920
Because you never know,
looking back on the footage,

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:27.110
there may be sections where
the audio isn't very clean.

00:06:27.110 --> 00:06:29.530
So you may have to rely
on your clean voiceover

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:30.390
for that section.

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:32.400
And maybe use B-roll to fill in.

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:34.150
If that makes sense to people.

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:36.720
Does anyone have
questions so far?

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:37.570
Yes.

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:40.210
AUDIENCE: Like you are filming,
and then you have a voice--

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:40.972
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:06:40.972 --> 00:06:43.305
AUDIENCE: --then you want to
use a voiceover separately.

00:06:43.305 --> 00:06:45.444
Then wouldn't the pacing off?

00:06:45.444 --> 00:06:46.110
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:06:46.110 --> 00:06:53.880
So for example we shot a
video, and part of it--

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:56.770
I'll talk more about it during
the editing lecture next week,

00:06:56.770 --> 00:06:59.550
but if you can find a
clean place to transition

00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:03.150
between the live footage
and your voiceover,

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:04.950
that's like the best
way to do that if you

00:07:04.950 --> 00:07:10.040
find that some of your footage
just has really bad live audio.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:13.030
For every place
that you shoot, I

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:15.900
recommend that you get room
tone, which is basically

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:17.660
the natural sound of the room.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:21.120
So for example, if you were
going to shoot in this room,

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:23.950
you would shoot the scene, and
then you would take your mic

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:26.627
and just record 30 seconds
where everyone's quiet.

00:07:26.627 --> 00:07:28.460
And it's just going to
record the background

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:30.150
noise of the room.

00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:35.210
And you do that because if
there is a case where you're

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:37.380
relying on voiceover
that you shot later,

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.824
or you're cutting bits and
pieces from the footage

00:07:40.824 --> 00:07:42.240
that you shot in
this room, you're

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:44.240
going to have this
gap or a hiccup

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:47.230
where the hum doesn't
exist, and it's

00:07:47.230 --> 00:07:49.080
going to sound really
awkward in the video.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:52.140
So you layer the room
tone underneath when

00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:54.400
you're editing so that you
don't have those hiccups

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:57.130
between the cuts that you make.

00:07:57.130 --> 00:07:58.800
GUEST SPEAKER: It's
kind of a decision

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:01.391
that you have to make,
too, based on the room.

00:08:01.391 --> 00:08:04.690
So like with Jeff, we actually
did the voiceover in the room.

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:08.550
Because it had a hum,
so we could have done

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:09.800
a better job of the voiceover.

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:13.090
But what we decided was that it
would be more jarring if there

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:15.960
was a major audio quality
difference between the voice

00:08:15.960 --> 00:08:18.650
over and the on
camera, you know,

00:08:18.650 --> 00:08:22.560
had we done it in a studio
or in a better space later.

00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:26.300
So, you know, it was clean
enough, we accepted it.

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:28.450
And that's why we
had him do everything

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:30.720
on the spot in the same
place, so that it wouldn't

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.034
have that drop in and out.

00:08:32.034 --> 00:08:32.700
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:33.991
Does that make sense to people?

00:08:33.991 --> 00:08:38.059
Like if we took the footage,
like this footage where

00:08:38.059 --> 00:08:40.820
I'm talking here, and then
we cut to something where

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:43.970
I continue to talk
about this class,

00:08:43.970 --> 00:08:45.940
but I was doing it
over a voiceover,

00:08:45.940 --> 00:08:48.610
and we had some B-roll
of you guys working.

00:08:48.610 --> 00:08:51.157
The first scene, you
would hear the hum,

00:08:51.157 --> 00:08:52.240
and you'd hear me talking.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:54.010
But in the second
scene, you would just

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:57.860
hear like very clean dead
space while I'm talking.

00:08:57.860 --> 00:09:00.030
And you would see
you guys working.

00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:02.250
And it would sound
and look really weird.

00:09:02.250 --> 00:09:04.146
It would feel really
weird to watch.

00:09:04.146 --> 00:09:06.430
GUEST SPEAKER: So we
just did another video

00:09:06.430 --> 00:09:09.504
not unlike the
[INAUDIBLE] video,

00:09:09.504 --> 00:09:11.670
except that the person is
in Kendall Square talking.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:13.870
All the on camera stuff
was in Kendall Square.

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:16.600
And that's really
noisy, so we decided in

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:17.820
that case to do the opposite.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:21.404
We didn't have him record
everything in Kendall Square,

00:09:21.404 --> 00:09:23.820
because then we would be dealing
with problems throughout.

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:27.280
But what we did is we recorded
the equivalent of room tone.

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:30.800
We just got audio
of Kendall Square,

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:33.780
and then we were able to
sort of slowly fade it out

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:35.530
after the person was
on camera, so that it

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:36.790
was more imperceptible.

00:09:36.790 --> 00:09:39.810
And then slowly fade it
back in before an on camera

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:42.028
arrived-- you know, comes back.

00:09:42.028 --> 00:09:43.986
AUDIENCE: There's no way
you can filter it out?

00:09:43.986 --> 00:09:45.880
Just kind of--

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:47.650
GUEST SPEAKER: Well
you can filter audio.

00:09:47.650 --> 00:09:50.640
What I always tell
people is don't.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.220
Especially like,
if you're not going

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:53.900
to spend thousands
of dollars doing it,

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:56.790
don't think you can do a lot.

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:59.930
There are a lot of consumer
tools that are available.

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:02.760
They generally really
degrade the voice.

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:06.172
Everyone ends up sounding
like I'm Stephen Hawking.

00:10:06.172 --> 00:10:08.380
PROFESSOR: Because the
frequencies in the room tone--

00:10:08.380 --> 00:10:09.500
GUEST SPEAKER:
Very similar, yeah.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:11.583
PROFESSOR: --some of the
frequencies in the voice.

00:10:11.583 --> 00:10:15.350
GUEST SPEAKER: So very,
very high end, very time

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:18.890
consuming tools are
out there to do it.

00:10:18.890 --> 00:10:21.509
But they're out of reach.

00:10:21.509 --> 00:10:23.550
PROFESSOR: Music can help
hide that a little bit,

00:10:23.550 --> 00:10:26.560
and I'm going to show you guys
examples of that next week.

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:29.620
But in general like it literally
takes 30 seconds for you

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:30.620
to record the room tone.

00:10:30.620 --> 00:10:31.660
So that's--

00:10:31.660 --> 00:10:32.350
GUEST SPEAKER: Yeah,
it's definitely worth it.

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:33.730
PROFESSOR: --It's worth it.

00:10:33.730 --> 00:10:38.580
So in general, as
a producer you're

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:41.450
doing a lot of anticipatory
thinking, which

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:43.170
is to help you
ultimately realize

00:10:43.170 --> 00:10:45.720
your big vision for your video.

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:47.660
So you're doing all
of these checklists,

00:10:47.660 --> 00:10:49.240
you're thinking ahead of time.

00:10:49.240 --> 00:10:51.573
Even in pre-production, which
is where we are right now,

00:10:51.573 --> 00:10:53.130
where you're scripting.

00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:55.800
As a producer you're going to be
thinking about the big picture

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:57.210
the entire time.

00:10:57.210 --> 00:10:59.810
So producing is really
looking at the big picture.

00:10:59.810 --> 00:11:02.560
You're looking at how the
microscopic decisions like,

00:11:02.560 --> 00:11:04.380
where you're going to
shoot for instance,

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.390
or where are you going
to record the room tone,

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:09.810
how that all fits into
your macroscopic plan.

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:12.930
So as Chris said, it's really
important to scout locations.

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:16.180
And when you go scout locations,
the two big things to look at

00:11:16.180 --> 00:11:18.307
are what's the lighting
like at that place,

00:11:18.307 --> 00:11:19.390
and what's the sound like?

00:11:19.390 --> 00:11:22.360
And when you're
looking at lighting,

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:23.830
not only look at
the natural light

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:26.890
that's available in the room,
if it's indoors for example,

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:28.730
but how the sunlight
affects the room.

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:32.950
So when we were pre-producing
this OpenCourseWare class,

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:34.700
we came and scouted
this classroom.

00:11:34.700 --> 00:11:37.160
And we noticed that there
are all these big windows,

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:38.712
and it was an afternoon class.

00:11:38.712 --> 00:11:40.420
And I knew that the
lighting in this room

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:42.330
would be really
different at 1 o'clock

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:44.320
than it would be at 4 o'clock.

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:47.020
So we decided that it actually
wouldn't be too big of a deal,

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:48.767
because people
watching the video

00:11:48.767 --> 00:11:51.100
wouldn't be like, oh my gosh
it's dark in that classroom

00:11:51.100 --> 00:11:52.720
now, that doesn't
make any sense.

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:54.920
Because obviously we know
it's a three hour class.

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:56.420
GUEST SPEAKER:
You'll notice Billy's

00:11:56.420 --> 00:11:58.500
on that side of the room,
not on this side of the room.

00:11:58.500 --> 00:11:59.166
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:11:59.166 --> 00:12:01.675
GUEST SPEAKER: That's
because if Elizabeth

00:12:01.675 --> 00:12:03.140
was teaching in
that corner, we'd

00:12:03.140 --> 00:12:05.730
have a problem with the windows.

00:12:05.730 --> 00:12:07.780
PROFESSOR: And we thought
about if we should just

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:10.874
lower the shades the entire time
so we have uniform lighting.

00:12:10.874 --> 00:12:12.290
So those are the
kind of questions

00:12:12.290 --> 00:12:14.248
that you'll ask yourself
during pre-production.

00:12:16.100 --> 00:12:18.480
And sound, again,
take room tone.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:20.720
The biggest sound issues
if you're outdoors,

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:22.990
the wind makes a big difference.

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:25.852
Most of you guys are going to
just rely on your lavaliers,

00:12:25.852 --> 00:12:27.060
and they have the little cap.

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:28.750
And that does a
generally good job,

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.678
but just take note of
it when you go scout.

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:36.322
My personal tip is
look for outlets.

00:12:36.322 --> 00:12:38.030
That's always been
like the biggest thing

00:12:38.030 --> 00:12:41.540
for us is, especially if it's
an outdoor location, scouting

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:44.120
ahead of time and seeing
how many outlets there are

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.150
helps you anticipate
how many extension

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:47.150
cords you need to bring.

00:12:47.150 --> 00:12:49.390
Which sounds like a silly
thing, but actually makes

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:52.530
a huge difference.

00:12:52.530 --> 00:12:55.300
So for example we
shot this video

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:58.480
with Jamie in the Stata
Center on computer switches.

00:12:58.480 --> 00:13:00.210
And we were with the Digi-Comp.

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:01.770
Or the Digi-Cart?

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:02.920
Digi-Comp.

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:06.340
Which we couldn't move, so we
had to shoot in this location.

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:08.980
And it was in Stata so we
knew it would be really noisy.

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:12.390
So we shot at like 6:00
in the morning on Sunday,

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:14.220
when no one would be around.

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:16.090
But the thing that
we didn't anticipate,

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:20.510
because I didn't scout that
location, which is bad,

00:13:20.510 --> 00:13:25.310
is that there's a skylight right
above the Digi-Comp-- I always

00:13:25.310 --> 00:13:26.800
forget what it's called.

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:30.410
So noon hit, and we had to
stop filming because there

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:32.580
was sunlight directly
overhead that

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:36.660
completely changed the shadows
on the prop, and on Jamie.

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:39.810
So we basically lost two
hours of shooting time

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:43.730
because we were waiting for
the sun to pass overhead.

00:13:43.730 --> 00:13:47.020
So that's why you should scout
your locations ahead of time.

00:13:47.020 --> 00:13:50.630
A quick note on locations,
also look at backgrounds.

00:13:50.630 --> 00:13:54.410
And with backgrounds you
should really be deliberate.

00:13:54.410 --> 00:13:55.730
And go big or go home.

00:13:55.730 --> 00:13:58.460
So for example,
this is a background

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:00.050
that I think a lot
of people default

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:02.810
to when they don't really
have anything else to shoot,

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:05.170
because they just sit-in
their office and they're like,

00:14:05.170 --> 00:14:06.795
I need to record
something really fast,

00:14:06.795 --> 00:14:08.620
I'll just sit here.

00:14:08.620 --> 00:14:11.470
Sitting in front of a
window that has blinds on it

00:14:11.470 --> 00:14:15.760
is maybe the worst possible
background that you could use.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:17.700
And again, this is a
matter of personal taste,

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:21.450
but I cringe when I see
this for two reasons.

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:24.420
One, it's really back-lit,
which is what Chris

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:25.990
was talking about earlier.

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:28.400
So you'll have so
much outdoor light

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:32.180
that it makes your
subjects look really dark.

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:34.560
And having all the
blinds in the background,

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:38.920
I think having all those lines
is really distracting as well.

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:41.240
This is what
happened when George

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:44.010
tried to change the exposure
setting on the camera

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:45.120
to light for me.

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:47.180
So I'm lit well, but
now the background

00:14:47.180 --> 00:14:48.690
is completely blown out.

00:14:48.690 --> 00:14:52.730
So in general, avoid filming
right in front of a window

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:55.232
where there is direct
sunlight coming in.

00:14:55.232 --> 00:14:56.940
And please don't film
in front of blinds.

00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:03.080
If anyone is
interested in filming

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:07.160
in front of a green
screen, it's possible,

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:08.825
and I'm happy to help you.

00:15:08.825 --> 00:15:11.200
I think you should be very
deliberate with that decision.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:13.050
Sometimes it works really well.

00:15:13.050 --> 00:15:14.082
This is an example.

00:15:14.082 --> 00:15:15.790
FEMALE IN VIDEO: So
in order to turn red,

00:15:15.790 --> 00:15:18.260
neurons from the squid's
brain sends signals

00:15:18.260 --> 00:15:21.410
to these muscles, which pull
open all of his chromatophores

00:15:21.410 --> 00:15:24.140
at the same time.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:26.751
PROFESSOR: So-- oh,
this was the wrong clip.

00:15:26.751 --> 00:15:27.250
Sorry guys.

00:15:27.250 --> 00:15:29.090
But there is one
example where she

00:15:29.090 --> 00:15:32.450
says, take note, when I
walk next to the squid,

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:33.380
he turns red.

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:35.572
And so you actually see
her walking on screen,

00:15:35.572 --> 00:15:36.780
and then the squid turns red.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:38.900
And so we used a green
screen to film this

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:40.610
because we like
the actual visual

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:46.980
of seeing some sort of
object stimulating the squid

00:15:46.980 --> 00:15:48.700
to turn colors.

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:51.230
So that's an example of a
green screen working well,

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:52.310
I think in my opinion.

00:15:52.310 --> 00:15:55.370
If you want to do something like
that, I'm happy to help you.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:57.290
But again, you
don't have to do it.

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:05.910
So more production tips.

00:16:05.910 --> 00:16:09.420
Days before, make sure
you scout your locations.

00:16:09.420 --> 00:16:10.800
A word about props.

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:12.840
So props don't have
to be expensive.

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:15.000
And I'm not just talking
about props on screen.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.100
I'm also talking about the
tools that you can use to film.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:21.310
So we're giving you a
tripod, and that's basically

00:16:21.310 --> 00:16:24.880
your only production prop.

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:28.590
But as Chris was saying,
like you can use desk lamps

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.290
with paper over them.

00:16:32.877 --> 00:16:33.960
Let me show you this shot.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:35.501
FEMALE IN VIDEO:
Let me show you how.

00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:46.300
PROFESSOR: So those are
all dolly shots basically,

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:49.600
of us establishing the
location of this video, which

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:52.900
is in D lab, which
is where Jack works.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:56.210
And they're all very smooth
pans of looking around

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:57.390
at the locations.

00:16:57.390 --> 00:17:00.590
And we shot that with
a cart, like a hand

00:17:00.590 --> 00:17:03.800
cart that I just sat in,
and George pushed me around.

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:06.460
So you could buy a
super expensive dolly,

00:17:06.460 --> 00:17:09.670
or you can just borrow a
cart from our department,

00:17:09.670 --> 00:17:14.390
and sit-in it, and have
someone push you around.

00:17:14.390 --> 00:17:16.339
The dolly is always
nicer, but we

00:17:16.339 --> 00:17:17.650
don't have the budget for that.

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:20.108
GUEST SPEAKER: Great job with
steady camerawork by the way.

00:17:20.108 --> 00:17:23.010
It can be an issue if
you're sitting on a cart,

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:24.670
if you start getting
a lot of this,

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:28.229
it takes away from the
niceness of the shot.

00:17:28.229 --> 00:17:29.700
But in this case it was great.

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:32.690
PROFESSOR: We took a
tripod and spread the legs

00:17:32.690 --> 00:17:34.830
out all the way, so that
it was like really, really

00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:36.330
firm in the cart.

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:39.539
And then I held it just
to add more stability.

00:17:39.539 --> 00:17:41.080
So it's possible
this is another one.

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:43.413
FEMALE IN VIDEO: To figure
out how the entire metabolome

00:17:43.413 --> 00:17:45.220
works, we can use it
to engineer plants

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:48.520
to create new bio-materials,
medicines, and clean energy.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:50.190
We might even discover
that plants have

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:52.050
the secret to living forever.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:55.211
We just need to unlock
their chemical mysteries.

00:17:55.211 --> 00:17:57.460
PROFESSOR: So that's actually
one of my favorite shots

00:17:57.460 --> 00:17:59.420
from Science Out Loud, ever.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:02.360
And that was all George's idea,
so I have to give him credit.

00:18:02.360 --> 00:18:03.950
But I like it because
it's a reveal,

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:05.160
like Chris was talking about.

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:06.493
It's the way we ended the video.

00:18:06.493 --> 00:18:08.800
We start off on the
plants, focused on it,

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:12.120
and you reveal
Anastasia at the end.

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:14.650
And that's actually-- to
get that smooth movement is

00:18:14.650 --> 00:18:15.760
actually really hard.

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:18.950
You might be able to do
it with these tripods

00:18:18.950 --> 00:18:22.510
because the cameras
aren't really heavy.

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:24.930
And you could probably get
enough friction on them

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:26.610
to get it to work.

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:30.730
But what we did was, George was
using a camera like that one.

00:18:30.730 --> 00:18:40.550
So he took the tripod, flipped
the top head of it upside down,

00:18:40.550 --> 00:18:44.340
and then he took a boom
pole, which is basically

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:47.650
this long pole, and put a
weight on one end of it,

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:50.230
and put the camera on the
other, and just slowly let

00:18:50.230 --> 00:18:53.440
the camera come up
from the weight.

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:58.110
So I'm all about MacGyvering
props if you need to.

00:18:58.110 --> 00:19:01.260
There are creative ways to
get around things and achieve

00:19:01.260 --> 00:19:04.660
nice effects with
cheaper equipment.

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:06.320
The other thing
about days before

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:09.390
is that you should make a shot
list, which is something that I

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:11.200
would like you guys to submit.

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:13.380
I think originally
I had specified

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:14.940
you to do that tonight.

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:18.490
But it's not necessary to do
it and post it until next week.

00:19:18.490 --> 00:19:20.890
So I'll update you
with another email.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:22.780
But a shot list is
basically what it says.

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:25.020
It's a list of all the
shots that you need.

00:19:25.020 --> 00:19:27.540
So it doesn't have to
look a certain way.

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:29.010
It's for your benefit only.

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:31.790
So organize it however
you think is best for you.

00:19:31.790 --> 00:19:34.650
But this was my shot
list for the reshoots

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:36.970
that we did for the snots video.

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:38.280
This is the first page of it.

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:41.810
So I listed out
all the locations

00:19:41.810 --> 00:19:44.680
that we were going to, what
time approximately we were going

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:47.200
to use it, so that I could
get a good sense of what

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:50.180
the lighting would look
like in these locations.

00:19:50.180 --> 00:19:54.100
And then I listed out exactly
what lines I needed to say,

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:57.330
and what shots we needed
to get at each location.

00:19:57.330 --> 00:20:00.690
And then at the bottom I
specified the wardrobe.

00:20:00.690 --> 00:20:03.550
So this is a super helpful
organizational tool

00:20:03.550 --> 00:20:06.710
to use when you're
planning things.

00:20:06.710 --> 00:20:09.800
When you are thinking
about locations,

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:11.940
definitely go big or go home.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:14.060
You can e-mail anyone
and just tell them

00:20:14.060 --> 00:20:16.430
you're doing a project
for a class at MIT,

00:20:16.430 --> 00:20:19.510
and you'd be surprised
what you could get.

00:20:19.510 --> 00:20:22.520
We shot at a horse
farm in Acton.

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:24.580
We shot in an airplane.

00:20:24.580 --> 00:20:27.320
We shot at a skydiving zone.

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:31.720
We shot at the butterfly exhibit
at the Museum of Science.

00:20:31.720 --> 00:20:33.120
Most of the labs
here, especially

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:36.477
since you're students, are going
to be super open to having you.

00:20:36.477 --> 00:20:38.060
And again that's
like your opportunity

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:40.040
to create a window into a
world that most people don't

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:40.900
have access to.

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:42.680
So definitely take
advantage of that.

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:45.720
If you have any issues
getting into a location,

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:46.450
just let me know.

00:20:49.850 --> 00:20:52.230
The day before, check
all your equipment.

00:20:52.230 --> 00:20:54.330
Check the batteries,
that's the biggest thing.

00:20:54.330 --> 00:20:55.310
Bring spare batteries.

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:57.890
If you need spare
batteries let me know.

00:20:57.890 --> 00:20:59.670
Double check your locations.

00:20:59.670 --> 00:21:01.130
If you're meeting
people, make sure

00:21:01.130 --> 00:21:02.566
that they know
that you're coming.

00:21:02.566 --> 00:21:03.482
And check the weather.

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:07.650
And then day of.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:12.350
So to help keep you organized
I recommend that you use

00:21:12.350 --> 00:21:14.090
camera reports or log sheets.

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:16.900
And what that looks
like, and again you

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:19.470
can set this up however you
think is most useful to you

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:20.040
to use.

00:21:20.040 --> 00:21:21.770
These are the camera
reports that we

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:23.180
use for Science Out Loud.

00:21:23.180 --> 00:21:25.130
But basically it's
to help us keep track

00:21:25.130 --> 00:21:28.670
of what video file is what.

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:31.180
And when you're shooting
like for six days straight,

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:32.580
this is really important.

00:21:32.580 --> 00:21:35.600
It may not be as vital to you,
but it'll be really useful

00:21:35.600 --> 00:21:36.890
when you go into edit.

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:40.710
But it's basically saying,
this video file was scene two,

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:41.750
take two.

00:21:41.750 --> 00:21:42.962
I thought it was OK.

00:21:42.962 --> 00:21:44.420
There were two good
takes in there.

00:21:44.420 --> 00:21:47.610
The last one was the best.

00:21:47.610 --> 00:21:49.077
Make sense to everyone?

00:21:49.077 --> 00:21:50.660
Let me know if you
have any questions.

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:54.570
Yeah.

00:21:54.570 --> 00:21:57.760
That's pretty straightforward.

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:01.380
And I would also recommend
looking at the dailies.

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:05.006
So I guess dailies
refers to all the footage

00:22:05.006 --> 00:22:06.130
that you take during a day.

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:08.984
Like maybe during a movie
production or a TV production.

00:22:08.984 --> 00:22:10.400
And the dailies
for you guys would

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:12.730
be like, at the
end of the day look

00:22:12.730 --> 00:22:16.860
through all the video footage
that you have on your camera

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:18.740
and just take note
of what you shot.

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:20.750
Make sure that it's good.

00:22:20.750 --> 00:22:23.820
What you don't want is to
shoot your entire episode

00:22:23.820 --> 00:22:27.280
and realize that the camera
settings had somehow muted you

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:29.240
and so you didn't
have any audio.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:33.320
So that's why looking at
the dailies is important.

00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:36.297
Also back up and label
all your files like right

00:22:36.297 --> 00:22:37.630
after you get back from a shoot.

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:42.969
So the biggest production
piece of advice,

00:22:42.969 --> 00:22:44.760
or like heads up that
I would give you guys

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:46.900
is that it takes a lot of time.

00:22:46.900 --> 00:22:49.260
Even if the
locations are scouted

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:54.650
and everything's sort of
organized perfectly the day of,

00:22:54.650 --> 00:22:57.970
you're going to take-- you're
going to do a lot of takes.

00:22:57.970 --> 00:23:02.360
Even if the person says
the line perfectly,

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:04.500
try a bunch of deliveries.

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:07.370
So remember how George
was saying like,

00:23:07.370 --> 00:23:09.420
say it really loud!

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:11.510
Now say it like however
you want, right?

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:14.020
And you got a different style.

00:23:14.020 --> 00:23:16.407
Try a bunch of deliveries.

00:23:16.407 --> 00:23:18.740
Try a different bunch of point
of views with the camera.

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:21.300
So maybe you shoot
someone straight on,

00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:23.680
then you try something
from the side.

00:23:23.680 --> 00:23:27.166
You try a different movement.

00:23:27.166 --> 00:23:29.040
And then like try
different types of framing.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:31.830
And Chris's piece
of advice, which

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:35.650
was like, most people tend
to not get enough footage

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:37.760
than get too much,
is really true.

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:39.760
Shoot like you're going
to use everything,

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:41.259
and then when you
edit, you're going

00:23:41.259 --> 00:23:43.480
to edit it like you're not
going to keep anything.

00:23:43.480 --> 00:23:45.660
But when you're
shooting, you always

00:23:45.660 --> 00:23:49.080
want to have more to work with,
because the worst feeling is

00:23:49.080 --> 00:23:51.530
when you're sitting,
editing, and you're like,

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:53.570
I wish I had shot x y z.

00:23:53.570 --> 00:23:55.610
It's the worst feeling.

00:23:55.610 --> 00:23:57.187
So it's going to
take a lot of time,

00:23:57.187 --> 00:23:59.270
because you want to create
as many options for you

00:23:59.270 --> 00:23:59.790
as you can.

