the best takes are the day of,

00:27:56.480 --> 00:27:59.180
you might watch it
a couple days later.

00:27:59.180 --> 00:28:01.730
And I recommend re-logging
everything and going

00:28:01.730 --> 00:28:03.480
through footage again later.

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:06.410
And you might find that
the thing that you liked

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:08.780
during the day of,
maybe you liked it

00:28:08.780 --> 00:28:11.304
because you were
starting to get tired,

00:28:11.304 --> 00:28:13.470
and it's going to look a
little bit different later.

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:16.650
So that's why I just
recommend the day after,

00:28:16.650 --> 00:28:18.017
just taking a step back.

00:28:21.430 --> 00:28:22.869
Let's see.

00:28:22.869 --> 00:28:23.368
Oh.

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:29.485
With the whole
multiple takes thing,

00:28:29.485 --> 00:28:31.860
I forgot to mention this
before, but I thought of it when

00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:33.340
you were doing your lecture.

00:28:33.340 --> 00:28:35.580
I would also
recommend doing takes

00:28:35.580 --> 00:28:39.490
from varying degrees of
separation from your subject.

00:28:39.490 --> 00:28:44.390
So say your host says, I'm
going to say this line,

00:28:44.390 --> 00:28:47.020
and you shoot it from
where Chris is standing.

00:28:47.020 --> 00:28:50.020
Even if the host like
nails the line perfectly,

00:28:50.020 --> 00:28:52.910
tell them to do it again
and shoot it from maybe

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:54.390
from where Yulia's standing.

00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:56.820
And tell them to do it again,
and shoot it from like right

00:28:56.820 --> 00:28:57.530
here.

00:28:57.530 --> 00:29:01.510
It's just good to have those
varying degrees of separation.

00:29:01.510 --> 00:29:06.640
It'll be easier to do the
zooming and everything in post.

00:29:06.640 --> 00:29:09.272
But again, having those
options to work with.

00:29:09.272 --> 00:29:10.980
You're not going to
know which one you're

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:14.130
going to use necessarily in
the moment that you're filming.

00:29:14.130 --> 00:29:16.172
So that's why it's good
to have a couple options.

00:29:16.172 --> 00:29:18.671
GUEST SPEAKER: The term is--
the technical term, not that it

00:29:18.671 --> 00:29:20.100
matters, is called, coverage.

00:29:20.100 --> 00:29:22.460
So basically, you
cover yourself.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:24.824
I don't really know how I'm
going to edit this together,

00:29:24.824 --> 00:29:26.740
so I'm going to give
myself as many choices as

00:29:26.740 --> 00:29:27.823
possible in the edit room.

00:29:27.823 --> 00:29:33.880
Because even the best directors
don't know exactly what

00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:34.420
they want.

00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:38.060
I mean there's Alfred Hitchcock
supposedly only filmed

00:29:38.060 --> 00:29:39.750
exactly what he wanted.

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:42.230
And his editors went insane
because they could only

00:29:42.230 --> 00:29:43.520
do one way.

00:29:43.520 --> 00:29:45.910
But pretty much
everyone else who's

00:29:45.910 --> 00:29:51.947
ever worked at any level in
film and video does coverage.

