00:32:38.280 --> 00:32:39.290
important places.

00:32:39.290 --> 00:32:41.300
There might be--

00:32:41.300 --> 00:32:45.240
PROFESSOR: So that's an example
of having zooms, but not

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:49.250
actually showing you zooming
with the camera, right?

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:51.860
And I think they do it
for a couple reasons.

00:32:51.860 --> 00:32:54.590
He probably-- he might have
messed up his line in between,

00:32:54.590 --> 00:32:57.050
and so that was a way to
sort of cut in between

00:32:57.050 --> 00:32:58.800
and not make the cuts
like super awkward,

00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:02.570
by having a zoom
in and a zoom out.

00:33:02.570 --> 00:33:05.730
And it's sort of like a rhythmic
visual pacing thing, too.

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:07.280
It cuts in like after he says--

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:09.196
GUEST SPEAKER: It's kind
of equivalent to, oh,

00:33:09.196 --> 00:33:12.190
different angle, pay attention.

00:33:12.190 --> 00:33:16.965
It's a different
convention than television,

00:33:16.965 --> 00:33:18.590
but it comes from a
very similar place.

00:33:18.590 --> 00:33:20.256
You know, if he was
just standing there,

00:33:20.256 --> 00:33:22.500
delivering without
edits, there'd

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:24.875
be this-- there's this terror
that you might turn away,

00:33:24.875 --> 00:33:26.360
and might not watch it.

00:33:26.360 --> 00:33:28.360
PROFESSOR: To
achieve that, though,

00:33:28.360 --> 00:33:30.860
if you wanted to do something
like that, I would say,

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:34.460
again, you could even
film this with a tripod

00:33:34.460 --> 00:33:35.660
and film yourself.

00:33:35.660 --> 00:33:38.270
But I would shoot
yourself-- that sounds

00:33:38.270 --> 00:33:41.590
weird-- I would take the camera
and put it on tripod like that

00:33:41.590 --> 00:33:44.330
far away, deliver
your whole sentence,

00:33:44.330 --> 00:33:47.440
and then move it forward and
deliver the whole thing again.

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:48.940
Because you don't
know exactly where

00:33:48.940 --> 00:33:49.975
you're going to cut into that.

00:33:49.975 --> 00:33:50.540
GUEST SPEAKER:
And that's clearly

00:33:50.540 --> 00:33:52.210
what most people--
I mean, this is

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:54.626
a very conventional thing you
see on the web all the time.

00:33:54.626 --> 00:33:55.850
And that's how they film.

00:33:55.850 --> 00:33:58.252
You know, a bunch of takes
of wide, a bunch of takes

00:33:58.252 --> 00:34:00.690
of close, medium, whatever.

00:34:00.690 --> 00:34:01.314
Editing.

00:34:01.314 --> 00:34:02.730
PROFESSOR: But the
point is you're

00:34:02.730 --> 00:34:05.400
going to be saying the same
line multiple times, even

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:07.350
if you nail it.

00:34:07.350 --> 00:34:11.060
This is where a zoom might work.

00:34:11.060 --> 00:34:16.480
[VIDEO PLAYING]

00:34:16.480 --> 00:34:17.730
PROFESSOR: So I say, or is it.

00:34:17.730 --> 00:34:21.020
But we use the zoom there
intentionally to make it funny.

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:24.120
Which hopefully it'll read
funny in the actual thing.

00:34:24.120 --> 00:34:26.760
So again, there aren't
like hard and fast rules

00:34:26.760 --> 00:34:28.409
were you should never
ever use a zoom,

00:34:28.409 --> 00:34:30.200
or you should never
ever center the person,

00:34:30.200 --> 00:34:31.750
or you should never ever--

00:34:31.750 --> 00:34:32.389
GUEST SPEAKER:
It's interesting, I

00:34:32.389 --> 00:34:33.889
mean, you know, I
was thinking about

00:34:33.889 --> 00:34:37.080
that whole centering thing
after the other day, Monday.

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:38.980
And a lot of times
when people break

00:34:38.980 --> 00:34:42.190
those kind of traditional
rules, is for comedic effect.

00:34:42.190 --> 00:34:46.283
And center frame stuff
tends to read funny.

00:34:46.283 --> 00:34:47.949
And you see that in
movies all the time.

00:34:47.949 --> 00:34:49.239
If you start paying
attention to this.

00:34:49.239 --> 00:34:51.790
If you go to a comedy, things
tend to be more center frame

00:34:51.790 --> 00:34:53.389
than if it's a drama.

00:34:53.389 --> 00:34:56.159
And I think one of the
reasons that vlogs are often

00:34:56.159 --> 00:34:58.320
center framed is that,
even if they're not funny,

00:34:58.320 --> 00:34:59.680
that's the affect.

00:34:59.680 --> 00:35:03.590
It's like this is amusing, this
is light, this is not scary.

00:35:03.590 --> 00:35:06.000
And that's why
people center frame.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:07.416
And you know, you can, too.

00:35:07.416 --> 00:35:08.328
If you want to.

