Yeah, so this is eventually
how we asked the students

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:13.040
to format their scripts.

00:37:13.040 --> 00:37:15.610
You don't have to
do that for Monday,

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:17.590
but eventually you're
going to want to do it.

00:37:17.590 --> 00:37:21.290
I think it makes organizing
things a lot easier.

00:37:21.290 --> 00:37:23.360
So it's just like a
four column format,

00:37:23.360 --> 00:37:27.660
where you specify what scene
number it is, the location.

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:29.700
So OS just means on screen.

00:37:29.700 --> 00:37:31.860
It means like you're
not going to B-roll,

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:34.340
you're just going to
be delivering it live.

00:37:34.340 --> 00:37:36.360
Just a description of
what the video looks like,

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:37.805
and what the script is itself.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:43.680
And if you share it
to me on Google Docs,

00:37:43.680 --> 00:37:48.520
it just makes it easier
for me to comment for you.

00:37:48.520 --> 00:37:51.530
And George also said that we
will give script feedbacks

00:37:51.530 --> 00:37:52.470
this weekend too.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:57.350
So if you can e-mail us this
stuff by Saturday at noon,

00:37:57.350 --> 00:38:01.955
we can give you lots of
feedback before Monday.

00:38:01.955 --> 00:38:05.326
AUDIENCE: I have another tip
that I usually forget about

00:38:05.326 --> 00:38:07.700
because I'm not used to talking
for long periods of time,

00:38:07.700 --> 00:38:10.150
and you guys will probably
get tired at some point

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:10.900
while filming.

00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:14.220
Bring a water bottle
and probably snacks too,

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:15.320
if you get hungry easily.

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:17.860
Just because when your
voice gets really dry

00:38:17.860 --> 00:38:20.910
and starts cracking, that might
ruin a take that otherwise

00:38:20.910 --> 00:38:23.160
went really, really well.

00:38:23.160 --> 00:38:25.442
And it helps with the
consistency of your voice.

00:38:25.442 --> 00:38:26.900
And you can edit
together something

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.150
that you did later with
something that you did earlier

00:38:29.150 --> 00:38:32.350
if your voice sounds
like consistently fresh

00:38:32.350 --> 00:38:33.420
throughout it.

00:38:33.420 --> 00:38:36.150
Because I've had problems
trying to edit audio

00:38:36.150 --> 00:38:39.580
where at the end of it, my
voice is really, really raspy.

00:38:39.580 --> 00:38:41.122
And at the beginning
it's still good.

00:38:41.122 --> 00:38:42.705
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
that's a great point.

00:38:42.705 --> 00:38:44.230
I'm glad you brought that up.

00:38:44.230 --> 00:38:46.210
So we try to cram
everything in as much

00:38:46.210 --> 00:38:49.510
as we can, which is purely
because of logistical issues,

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:51.250
and because of our budget.

00:38:51.250 --> 00:38:53.190
But you're going
to have the time

00:38:53.190 --> 00:38:54.784
this month to where
you're not going

00:38:54.784 --> 00:38:56.700
to have to shoot your
entire video in one day.

00:38:56.700 --> 00:38:58.740
So really try to spread
it out over the course

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:00.270
of several days.

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:02.436
And that's built
into the class time.

00:39:02.436 --> 00:39:04.310
But I will just say from
personal experience,

00:39:04.310 --> 00:39:09.840
it is so incredibly difficult
to film for more than five

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:10.970
or six hours straight.

00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:14.520
You just get really, really
exhausted by the end of it.

00:39:14.520 --> 00:39:16.070
OK.

